"""
MKT Christ-in-Every-Verse Commentary — Genesis chapters 38–40
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-genesis-38-40.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/genesis.json (verse inventory: ch38=30v, ch39=23v, ch40=23v; total 76)
- data/translation/draft/mediating/genesis.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/genesis.json (existing; merge_comm skips present entries)

Key Christological decisions:
- 38: Tamar appears in Matt 1:3 (Christ's genealogy). The entire chapter is a
  canonical-context revelation of how the Messianic line runs through moral failure and
  scandal. "She is more righteous than I" (v26) is a type of justification: the accused
  declared righteous by the judge. The scarlet thread (v28) echoes Rahab (Josh 2:18-21)
  — both mark the one through whom salvation comes.
- 38: Judah's "going down" (v1, yarad) — the moral and geographical descent that
  nearly derails the Messianic line, contrasting with Joseph's descent into Egypt which
  becomes the means of salvation. The same verb used for going down in the Joseph story.
- 39: The repeated "LORD was with Joseph" (vv2, 3, 21, 23) — the divine-presence
  formula that marks Joseph as the covenant-bearer through suffering. Type of Christ's
  divine presence even in suffering (John 8:29: "the one who sent me is with me").
  Joseph's temptation-without-sin (Heb 4:15), false accusation (Matt 26:59-61), and
  prison where LORD shows hesed (v21) are the core Christ-type structural parallels.
- 40: The "three days" recurring twice (vv12, 18) — cupbearer restored/baker executed
  on the third day. Type of the resurrection and its two outcomes (John 5:28-29). The
  baker/cupbearer split is the type of the two criminals crucified with Christ (Luke
  23:39-43). "Remember me" (v14) echoes Luke 23:42. The cupbearer's forgetting (v23)
  is the type of human ingratitude toward the deliverer (Luke 17:17-18).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW_DATA = {
"38": {
"1": "<p>At that time, Judah left his brothers and went down to stay with a man of Adullam named Hirah &#8212; ch38 is the great narrative interruption: the Joseph story (begun in ch37 and resumed in ch39) is paused for the Judah-Tamar episode. The placement is deliberate. Judah &#8220;went down&#8221; (yarad &#8212; the same descent-verb used of Joseph going down to Egypt in 37:25, 28, 36; 39:1) at the moment the Joseph story requires its reader to see: the two brothers both &#8220;go down&#8221; &#8212; Joseph into slavery, Judah into moral compromise. Joseph&#8217;s descent becomes salvation; Judah&#8217;s descent nearly derails the Messianic line but is rescued by Tamar&#8217;s courageous faithfulness. Judah&#8217;s leaving his brothers is the covenant-bearer&#8217;s first act of separation from the covenant community &#8212; going to live among the Canaanites rather than within the family.</p>",
"2": "<p>There Judah met the daughter of a Canaanite man named Shua. He married her and slept with her &#8212; Judah&#8217;s Canaanite marriage &#8212; the same exogamy that Isaac and Jacob explicitly avoided (24:3; 28:1). The covenant patriarch who married within the covenant (endogamy) is replaced by a son who marries outside it. The narrative does not editorialize, but the contrast with the careful covenant endogamy of Abraham (who sent his servant to find a wife for Isaac from among his own people) makes the departure clear. Matthew&#8217;s genealogy (1:3) names the son of this union (Perez) as an ancestor of Christ, making the Canaanite union part of the Messianic line &#8212; the same inclusion of Canaanite outsiders (Rahab, the mother of Boaz) that the genealogy elsewhere celebrates.</p>",
"3": "<p>She became pregnant and gave birth to a son, who was named Er &#8212; the first son of Judah and the Canaanite woman. Er is the eldest who will be first in the line of succession but is wicked in the LORD&#8217;s sight (v7) and dies without offspring. The firstborn who fails to produce the covenant heir is the recurring pattern: Reuben (Leah&#8217;s firstborn, who forfeited his birthright), Ishmael (Abraham&#8217;s firstborn by Hagar), and now Er. The consistent failure of the natural firstborn to carry the covenant purpose is the type of the old covenant&#8217;s inability to produce the righteousness it promises: &#8220;For what the law was powerless to do&#8221; (Rom 8:3). The true Firstborn is Christ, who does not fail: &#8220;the firstborn over all creation&#8221; (Col 1:15).</p>",
"4": "<p>She conceived again and gave birth to a son and named him Onan &#8212; Onan, the second son who will also fail his covenant duty (v8&#8211;10) and die. The second son who carries the hope after the firstborn fails but then fails himself. The pattern of repeated human failure at the covenant&#8217;s demand is the OT&#8217;s honest account of the human condition: no generation solves the problem of the previous generation&#8217;s moral failure. Paul&#8217;s diagnosis: &#8220;for all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God&#8221; (Rom 3:23). The solution is not a better human heir but the divine heir who does not fail: &#8220;God sent his own Son in the likeness of sinful flesh to be a sin offering&#8221; (Rom 8:3).</p>",
"5": "<p>She gave birth to still another son and named him Shelah &#8212; Shelah, the third and youngest son. Judah&#8217;s three sons with his Canaanite wife are all (ultimately) unable to carry the Messianic line: Er dies wicked, Onan dies wicked, and Shelah is withheld from Tamar by Judah&#8217;s fear (v11). The Messianic line through Judah does not come through Judah&#8217;s Canaanite wife or any of her sons but through the unexpected union with Tamar &#8212; the daughter-in-law Judah himself had wronged. God&#8217;s covenant purposes consistently bypass the expected human channels. &#8220;The stone the builders rejected has become the cornerstone&#8221; (Ps 118:22; Matt 21:42) &#8212; the rejected and unexpected one becomes the foundation.</p>",
"6": "<p>Judah got a wife for Er, his firstborn, and her name was Tamar &#8212; Tamar is introduced as Er&#8217;s wife. Tamar &#8212; whose name means &#8220;palm tree&#8221; &#8212; is one of four women Matthew includes in Christ&#8217;s genealogy (Matt 1:3: &#8220;Judah the father of Perez and Zerah, whose mother was Tamar&#8221;). The other three are Rahab (the Canaanite prostitute), Ruth (the Moabite widow), and the wife of Uriah (Bathsheba, involved in David&#8217;s great sin). All four women are outsiders or associated with sexual scandal, yet all four are named in the genealogy of the Messiah. Matthew&#8217;s deliberate inclusion signals that the Messianic line does not run through moral tidiness but through grace that works through and despite human scandal.</p>",
"7": "<p>But Er, Judah&#8217;s firstborn, was wicked in the LORD&#8217;s sight; so the LORD put him to death &#8212; divine judgment on Er&#8217;s wickedness: the LORD acts directly to end Er&#8217;s life. The narrative does not specify Er&#8217;s sin but the divine verdict is clear: &#8220;wicked in the LORD&#8217;s sight.&#8221; The divine holiness that cannot tolerate unrepentant wickedness even within the covenant family is the same holiness that required the cross: &#8220;The wages of sin is death&#8221; (Rom 6:23). Christ takes this death-penalty upon himself: &#8220;God made him who had no sin to be sin for us, so that in him we might become the righteousness of God&#8221; (2 Cor 5:21). Er dies for his own sin; Christ dies for others&#8217; sin.</p>",
"8": "<p>Then Judah said to Onan, &#8220;Sleep with your brother&#8217;s wife and fulfill your duty to her as a brother-in-law to raise up offspring for your brother&#8221; &#8212; the levirate duty (from Latin levir = husband&#8217;s brother): the brother-in-law is to produce offspring for the dead brother&#8217;s line. The levirate law later codified in Deut 25:5&#8211;10 is operating here as a pre-Mosaic custom. The kinsman-redeemer who raises up offspring for the one who has died is the type of Christ the ultimate goel: Christ raises up new life (spiritual offspring) for those who were spiritually dead. The levirate logic &#8212; &#8220;the living must serve the dead man&#8217;s family to raise up life&#8221; &#8212; is exactly the pattern of the incarnation: the living God serves the spiritually dead to raise up new life through the resurrection.</p>",
"9": "<p>But Onan knew that the child would not be his; so whenever he slept with his brother&#8217;s wife, he spilled his semen on the ground &#8212; Onan&#8217;s deliberate refusal of the levirate duty: he takes the privileges of Tamar&#8217;s marriage without fulfilling the responsibility. The exploitation of a position&#8217;s benefits while refusing its obligations is the self-serving inversion of covenant. Christ describes the opposite: &#8220;whoever wants to become great among you must be your servant, and whoever wants to be first must be your slave&#8221; (Matt 20:26&#8211;27). The one who holds the position of kinsman-redeemer uses it for self-interest rather than the other&#8217;s benefit &#8212; the anti-type of Christ who uses his position as Son of God entirely for others&#8217; benefit (Phil 2:6&#8211;7: &#8220;he did not consider equality with God something to be used to his own advantage&#8221;).</p>",
"10": "<p>What he did was wicked in the LORD&#8217;s sight; so the LORD put him to death also &#8212; Onan&#8217;s death, like Er&#8217;s, is direct divine judgment. Two brothers dead, Tamar twice a widow, the Messianic line through Judah apparently broken. The narrative describes a situation of apparent covenant failure. The covenant line that seems broken is precisely where God typically acts: the barren womb, the dead son, the impossible situation. Heb 11:12: &#8220;And so from this one man, and he as good as dead, came descendants as numerous as the stars in the sky.&#8221; The apparently impossible situation is where divine action becomes visible. The death of both sons does not end the covenant line &#8212; it redirects it through the unexpected Tamar.</p>",
"11": "<p>Judah then said to his daughter-in-law Tamar, &#8220;Live as a widow in your father&#8217;s household until my son Shelah grows up.&#8221; For he thought, &#8220;He may die too, just like his brothers&#8221; &#8212; Judah&#8217;s protective lie: he withholds Shelah from Tamar out of fear that Shelah will also die. The self-protective deception that deprives Tamar of her covenant right is a form of injustice. Judah does not intend to give Shelah to Tamar (as v26 confirms); he uses Shelah&#8217;s youth as a pretext. The covenant leader&#8217;s failure to protect the vulnerable woman in his care is the moral failure that Jesus names: &#8220;He who is hired and not the shepherd, who does not own the sheep, sees the wolf coming and abandons them&#8221; (John 10:12). Judah is the hired hand who sends Tamar away rather than protecting her.</p>",
"12": "<p>After a long time Judah&#8217;s wife, the daughter of Shua, died. When Judah had recovered from his grief, he went up to Timnah, to the men who were shearing his sheep &#8212; Judah&#8217;s wife dies; after mourning, he goes to the sheep-shearing festival at Timnah. The sheep-shearing festival was a time of celebration, feasting, and (sometimes) sexual license in the ANE (cf. 1 Sam 25:2&#8211;11 where Nabal is shearing). Judah&#8217;s going up to Timnah after his wife&#8217;s death sets the scene for the encounter with Tamar. The covenant-bearer at a feast &#8212; vulnerable to temptation in a moment of grief and celebration &#8212; is the human context in which the covenant line&#8217;s near-failure occurs. The vulnerability of grief is the moment at which the covenant community&#8217;s moral vigilance most often fails.</p>",
"13": "<p>When Tamar was told, &#8220;Your father-in-law is on his way to Timnah to shear his sheep,&#8221; &#8212; Tamar receives intelligence of Judah&#8217;s movements. The information that allows Tamar to act is the type of the divine knowledge that enables timely action. Tamar&#8217;s plan is not random but precisely timed to Judah&#8217;s known movements. The providential alignment of circumstances that allows covenant purposes to be accomplished even through unusual means is the pattern of the incarnation&#8217;s timing: &#8220;when the set time had fully come, God sent his Son&#8221; (Gal 4:4). The precise timing of the divine action &#8212; &#8220;when Tamar was told&#8221; &#8212; mirrors the divine timing that governs all salvation history.</p>",
"14": "<p>She took off her widow&#8217;s clothes, covered herself with a veil to disguise herself, and sat down at the entrance to Enaim &#8212; Tamar&#8217;s disguise and positioning. The widow who disguises herself to secure the covenant right that has been withheld from her is acting in covenant faithfulness, not self-interest. The NT equivalent is the persistent widow of Luke 18:1&#8211;8 who pursues justice from an unjust judge without ceasing &#8212; a parable Jesus tells about persistent prayer. Tamar is the OT persistent widow who will not accept the unjust withholding of the covenant right. Her disguise is the means; her end is the covenant heir. Christ commends persistent pursuit of what is rightfully promised: &#8220;Keep asking, and it will be given to you; keep seeking, and you will find&#8221; (Matt 7:7).</p>",
"15": "<p>When Judah saw her, he thought she was a prostitute, for she had covered her face &#8212; Judah&#8217;s misidentification of Tamar. The one who should recognize his own daughter-in-law &#8212; the woman who has been living in his household &#8212; does not recognize her. The moral blindness that allows the self-deceived sinner to act without recognizing what he is doing is the condition that the gospel addresses: &#8220;For this people&#8217;s heart has become calloused; they hardly hear with their ears, and they have closed their eyes&#8221; (Matt 13:15, citing Isa 6:10). Judah is blind to Tamar&#8217;s identity; the sinner is blind to God&#8217;s claim. Christ comes to open the eyes of the blind, literally and spiritually (John 9:1&#8211;41).</p>",
"16": "<p>Not realizing that she was his daughter-in-law, he went over to her and said, &#8220;Come now, let me sleep with you.&#8221; &#8212; Judah&#8217;s approach to the one he thinks is a prostitute. The covenant patriarch seeking sex from a supposed shrine prostitute is the low point of the Judah narrative. But it becomes the unlikely means through which the Messianic line is preserved. God&#8217;s covenant purposes are not defeated by human sin; they are worked out through and despite it. &#8220;Where sin increased, grace increased all the more&#8221; (Rom 5:20). The sin that Judah commits is the very occasion through which Tamar secures what Judah had unjustly withheld. The cross itself is this pattern at its extreme: the greatest human sin (the murder of the Son of God) becomes the means of the greatest divine grace (the atonement for sin).</p>",
"17": "<p>&#8220;I&#8217;ll send you a young goat from my flock,&#8221; he said. &#8220;Will you give me something as a pledge until you send it?&#8221; she asked &#8212; the transaction: a goat as payment, a pledge as security. Tamar&#8217;s insistence on a pledge is the key to her plan &#8212; the pledge will be the evidence that convicts Judah of his own wrongdoing. The sinner&#8217;s own promises become the evidence of his guilt: the things given in moments of self-gratification become the testimony against self-serving judgment. Paul: &#8220;the evidence against you is clear&#8221; (Rom 2:1: &#8220;You, therefore, have no excuse, you who pass judgment on someone else, for at whatever point you judge another, you are condemning yourself&#8221;). Judah&#8217;s pledge &#8212; given in sin &#8212; is the very thing that will convict him when he passes judgment on Tamar.</p>",
"18": "<p>He said, &#8220;What pledge should I give you?&#8221; &#8220;Your seal and its cord, and the staff in your hand,&#8221; she answered. So he gave them to her and slept with her, and she became pregnant by him &#8212; Judah gives his seal, cord, and staff &#8212; the symbols of his personal identity and authority. The pledge of the seal, cord, and staff is the giving of everything that identified him as Judah: these are not minor personal items but the covenant leader&#8217;s authoritative tokens. The self-giving of the one who holds authority &#8212; giving the very symbols of his authority as a pledge &#8212; is the type of Christ&#8217;s self-giving: &#8220;he gave himself for us to redeem us&#8221; (Titus 2:14); &#8220;I lay down my life&#8212; no one takes it from me, but I lay it down of my own accord&#8221; (John 10:17&#8211;18). Judah gives himself in sin; Christ gives himself in love.</p>",
"19": "<p>After she left, she took off her veil and put on her widow&#8217;s clothes again &#8212; Tamar returns to her widow&#8217;s state, now carrying Judah&#8217;s child. The widow who has secured the covenant heir but must wait in obscurity for the revelation of what she has done. The waiting of the one who carries the covenant promise in secret is the type of the church in the period between the ascension and the return: carrying the life of Christ (&#8220;Christ in you, the hope of glory,&#8221; Col 1:27) in the plain clothes of ordinary life, waiting for the revelation. The time between the conception and the birth &#8212; the hidden pregnancy &#8212; is the type of the &#8220;already but not yet&#8221; of the gospel&#8217;s fulfillment.</p>",
"20": "<p>Meanwhile Judah sent the young goat by his friend the Adullamite in order to get his pledge back from the woman, but he did not find her &#8212; Judah&#8217;s attempt to retrieve his pledge fails: there is no shrine prostitute to be found. The irony is that the &#8220;shrine prostitute&#8221; he seeks does not exist &#8212; the woman was his own daughter-in-law. The pursuit of the wrong person in the wrong direction is the type of the human search for God conducted in the wrong place: &#8220;you will look for me, but you will not find me; and where I am, you cannot come&#8221; (John 7:34). The human search for what is desired &#8212; conducted through the wrong channels &#8212; ends in not finding. Christ is the one who makes the divine findable: &#8220;Seek and you will find&#8221; (Matt 7:7).</p>",
"21": "<p>He asked the men who lived there, &#8220;Where is the shrine prostitute who was beside the road at Enaim?&#8221; &#8220;There hasn&#8217;t been any shrine prostitute here,&#8221; they said &#8212; the local men confirm there is no shrine prostitute. The one Judah seeks does not exist as he imagined her. The mismatch between the person sought and the person found runs through the NT&#8217;s accounts of those who sought Jesus with wrong expectations: the disciples who expected a political Messiah found a suffering servant; the crowd who wanted a bread-king (John 6:15: &#8220;by force to make him king&#8221;) found one who gave himself as living bread. The one who is sought is always other than expected &#8212; which is why the encounter with Christ always involves the reordering of expectations.</p>",
"22": "<p>&#8220;I didn&#8217;t find her. Besides, the men who lived there said, &#8216;There hasn&#8217;t been any shrine prostitute here.&#8217;&#8221; &#8212; the report to Judah of the failed search. The failed mission to retrieve the pledge is the turning point: Judah cannot recover his identifying tokens. What he gave cannot be retrieved. The seal, cord, and staff that Judah gave remain with Tamar until the moment of revelation (v25). The things surrendered in a moment of sin cannot simply be retrieved &#8212; they remain as evidence. Christ&#8217;s sacrifice cannot be &#8220;retrieved&#8221; or undone either: &#8220;he appeared once for all at the culmination of the ages to do away with sin by the sacrifice of himself&#8221; (Heb 9:26). The giving is permanent &#8212; in Judah&#8217;s case to his own condemnation; in Christ&#8217;s case to the world&#8217;s salvation.</p>",
"23": "<p>Then Judah said, &#8220;Let her keep what she has, or we will become a laughingstock. After all, I did send her this young goat, but you didn&#8217;t find her&#8221; &#8212; Judah&#8217;s pragmatic abandonment of the pledge rather than pursuing the matter further. The fear of public exposure (&#8220;we will become a laughingstock&#8221;) motivates the abandonment. The sinner&#8217;s primary concern is not the sin but the public reputation: &#8220;they loved human praise more than praise from God&#8221; (John 12:43). Christ refuses this shame-management logic: &#8220;Whoever is ashamed of me and my words in this adulterous and sinful generation, the Son of Man will be ashamed of them&#8221; (Mark 8:38). The fear of the laughingstock rather than the fear of God is the mark of the self-deceived life.</p>",
"24": "<p>About three months later Judah was told, &#8220;Your daughter-in-law Tamar is guilty of prostitution, and as a result she is now pregnant.&#8221; Judah said, &#8220;Bring her out and have her burned!&#8221; &#8212; Judah&#8217;s harsh judgment on Tamar. The same man who hired a supposed prostitute now calls for his daughter-in-law to be executed for prostitution. The one who is guilty pronouncing judgment on the guilty other: &#8220;You, therefore, have no excuse, you who pass judgment on someone else, for at whatever point you judge another, you are condemning yourself, because you who pass judgment do the same things&#8221; (Rom 2:1). The hypocrisy of Judah&#8217;s &#8220;Bring her out!&#8221; is the type of the religious leaders who bring to Jesus &#8220;a woman caught in adultery&#8221; (John 8:3&#8211;5) while themselves guilty. In both cases, the judge is convicted.</p>",
"25": "<p>As she was being brought out, she sent a message to her father-in-law: &#8220;I am pregnant by the man who owns these.&#8221; And she added, &#8220;See if you recognize whose seal and cord and staff these are&#8221; &#8212; Tamar&#8217;s defense &#8212; not a verbal argument but physical evidence: the seal, cord, and staff. The evidence she presents is Judah&#8217;s own pledge &#8212; his own self-identification. The guilty man is confronted with his own identifying tokens in his own hand. &#8220;See if you recognize&#8221; &#8212; a deliberate echo of 37:32 where Joseph&#8217;s brothers showed Jacob Joseph&#8217;s bloody coat and said &#8220;See if you recognize&#8221; (haker na &#8212; the same phrase). The same words that Judah used to deceive his father (37:32) are now used to convict Judah. The deceiver is convicted by the deceiver&#8217;s own method: his own evidence, his own words.</p>",
"26": "<p>Judah recognized them and said, &#8220;She is more righteous than I, since I wouldn&#8217;t give her to my son Shelah.&#8221; And he did not sleep with her again &#8212; &#8220;She is more righteous than I&#8221; &#8212; one of the most remarkable statements in Genesis. The judge who was about to execute the accused declares her righteous and himself guilty. The reversal of the verdict is the type of justification: the condemned is declared righteous, the judge is convicted. Paul in Rom 3:21&#8211;26 describes the same reversal: God &#8220;justifies those who have faith in Jesus&#8221; &#8212; declaring righteous those who stand condemned. The woman brought forward for judgment who goes away justified &#8212; echoing John 8:10&#8211;11: &#8220;Has no one condemned you?&#8221; &#8220;No one, sir.&#8221; &#8220;Then neither do I condemn you.&#8221; The judge&#8217;s declaration of righteousness is the type of the divine acquittal through Christ.</p>",
"27": "<p>When the time came for her to give birth, there were twin boys in her womb &#8212; twins, like Jacob and Esau (25:24). The unexpected multiplicity &#8212; one son was expected; two come &#8212; is the divine overabundance that characterizes God&#8217;s blessing. &#8220;Now to him who is able to do immeasurably more than all we ask or imagine&#8221; (Eph 3:20). The birth of twins through Tamar &#8212; the unexpected doubling &#8212; is the type of the gospel&#8217;s abundance: more than what was asked or expected. The Messianic line was in danger of dying out through Judah&#8217;s moral failure; instead it produces twins &#8212; two ancestors rather than one &#8212; through the very failure that threatened it.</p>",
"28": "<p>As she was giving birth, one of them put out his hand; so the midwife took a scarlet thread and tied it on his wrist and said, &#8220;This one came out first&#8221; &#8212; the scarlet thread tied on Zerah&#8217;s wrist to mark the &#8220;firstborn.&#8221; The scarlet thread appears again in Josh 2:18&#8211;21 where Rahab ties a scarlet cord in the window to protect her household &#8212; both scarlet threads mark the one through whom salvation comes. In both cases, the scarlet (blood-red) marker signals the point of rescue and covenant inclusion. The red/scarlet color as a marker of the covenant-of-blood is the type of the blood of Christ that marks and protects: &#8220;the blood of Jesus, his Son, purifies us from all sin&#8221; (1 John 1:7). The scarlet thread at the birth of Tamar&#8217;s son anticipates the scarlet cord of Rahab which anticipates the blood of Christ.</p>",
"29": "<p>But when he drew back his hand, his brother came out, and she said, &#8220;So this is how you have broken out!&#8221; And he was named Perez &#8212; Perez (pereẓ = &#8220;breach/breaking out&#8221;) &#8212; the one who was not marked as first but breaks out first, overturning the established order. Perez is in Matthew&#8217;s genealogy (1:3; Luke 3:33) &#8212; the &#8220;breach-maker&#8221; is in the Messianic line. Christ is the ultimate Perez &#8212; the one who breaks through all human categories and expectations: &#8220;the stone the builders rejected has become the cornerstone&#8221; (Matt 21:42). The reversal of the expected birth order &#8212; Zerah marked first, Perez born first &#8212; is the consistent divine pattern: &#8220;the last will be first, and the first will be last&#8221; (Matt 20:16). The one who breaks out unexpectedly is the messianic ancestor.</p>",
"30": "<p>Then his brother, who had the scarlet thread on his wrist, came out. And he was named Zerah &#8212; Zerah (zerah = &#8220;shining/rising&#8221; &#8212; like the rising sun) is born second despite being marked first. Both Perez and Zerah are named in Matthew&#8217;s genealogy: &#8220;Judah the father of Perez and Zerah, whose mother was Tamar&#8221; (1:3). The scarlet-threaded Zerah, whose name means &#8220;brightness,&#8221; is a type of Christ as the sun of righteousness: &#8220;the sun of righteousness will rise with healing in its rays&#8221; (Mal 4:2). The Perez-and-Zerah pair &#8212; breach-maker and shining-one &#8212; capture two aspects of the Messiah: the one who breaks through human boundaries and the one who rises in light and healing. Both names belong in Christ&#8217;s genealogy because both aspects belong to Christ.</p>",
},
"39": {
"1": "<p>Now Joseph had been taken down to Egypt. Potiphar, an Egyptian who was one of Pharaoh&#8217;s officials, the captain of the guard, bought him from the Ishmaelites who had taken him there &#8212; the Joseph narrative resumes after the Judah-Tamar parenthesis. &#8220;Taken down to Egypt&#8221; (yarad &#8212; the same descent-verb) &#8212; Joseph&#8217;s descent is involuntary, as a slave. The purchased slave who was bought by Ishmael-traders from his own brothers: the betrayal-and-sale by brothers will become the foundational type of Christ&#8217;s betrayal. Acts 7:9&#8211;10: &#8220;Because the patriarchs were jealous of Joseph, they sold him as a slave into Egypt. But God was with him and rescued him from all his troubles.&#8221; The descent into Egypt as slave is the type of the incarnation&#8217;s descent: &#8220;he took the very nature of a servant, being made in human likeness&#8221; (Phil 2:7).</p>",
"2": "<p>The LORD was with Joseph so that he prospered, and he lived in the house of his Egyptian master &#8212; &#8220;The LORD was with Joseph&#8221; &#8212; the first of four occurrences in this chapter (vv2, 3, 21, 23). The divine presence formula that runs through Genesis: &#8220;I am with you and will watch over you wherever you go&#8221; (28:15, to Jacob). The God who is with the covenant-bearer even in the alien Egyptian household is the God whose presence cannot be contained by geography or circumstance. Christ promises the same: &#8220;And surely I am with you always, to the very end of the age&#8221; (Matt 28:20). John 8:29: &#8220;The one who sent me is with me; he has not left me alone.&#8221; The divine presence that was with Joseph through slavery is the presence that was with Christ through the cross.</p>",
"3": "<p>When his master saw that the LORD was with him and that the LORD gave him success in everything he did &#8212; Potiphar, a pagan Egyptian, recognizes that &#8220;the LORD was with him.&#8221; The covenant God&#8217;s presence is visible even to pagans through the covenant-bearer&#8217;s life. The Abrahamic blessing flowing to the surrounding world: &#8220;all peoples on earth will be blessed through you&#8221; (12:3). The visible evidence of divine presence that others can observe is the type of the church&#8217;s witness: &#8220;Let your light shine before others, that they may see your good deeds and glorify your Father in heaven&#8221; (Matt 5:16). Potiphar glorifies not God but his own household&#8217;s prosperity &#8212; but the recognition is there. The divine blessing through the covenant-bearer is visible to those who look.</p>",
"4": "<p>Joseph found favor in his eyes and became his attendant. Potiphar put him in charge of his household, and he entrusted to his care everything he owned &#8212; the slave who rises to steward the household through divine favor. The pattern of the faithful servant who is entrusted with &#8220;everything he owned&#8221; is the parable of the talents (Matt 25:21: &#8220;you have been faithful with a few things; I will put you in charge of many things&#8221;). The slave-steward given charge of everything is the type of Christ as the one to whom the Father has given all authority: &#8220;All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me&#8221; (Matt 28:18); &#8220;The Father loves the Son and has placed everything in his hands&#8221; (John 3:35). Joseph in Potiphar&#8217;s house is the type of Christ in the Father&#8217;s household.</p>",
"5": "<p>From the time Potiphar put him in charge of his household and of all that he owned, the LORD blessed the household of the Egyptian because of Joseph &#8212; the Egyptian&#8217;s household is blessed &#8220;because of Joseph.&#8221; The covenant-bearer&#8217;s presence is the channel of divine blessing to Gentile households &#8212; the exact form of the Abrahamic promise: &#8220;all peoples on earth will be blessed through you&#8221; (12:3). The blessing that comes to Potiphar&#8217;s household through Joseph&#8217;s presence is the type of the blessing that comes to all who receive Christ: &#8220;Praise be to the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ, who has blessed us in the heavenly realms with every spiritual blessing in Christ&#8221; (Eph 1:3). The blessing is &#8220;in Christ&#8221; &#8212; available to all who, like Potiphar&#8217;s household, receive the covenant-bearer.</p>",
"6": "<p>So Potiphar left everything he had in Joseph&#8217;s care; with Joseph in charge, he did not concern himself with anything except the food he ate. Now Joseph was well-built and handsome &#8212; the stewardship is so complete that Potiphar trusts Joseph with everything. The total entrustment &#8212; &#8220;did not concern himself with anything except the food he ate&#8221; &#8212; is the type of the Father&#8217;s entrustment of the world to the Son: &#8220;The Father judges no one, but has entrusted all judgment to the Son&#8221; (John 5:22); &#8220;the Father&#8230; has placed everything in his hands&#8221; (John 3:35). The description of Joseph as &#8220;well-built and handsome&#8221; &#8212; in contrast to the Servant&#8217;s description (&#8220;no beauty or majesty to attract us to him,&#8221; Isa 53:2) &#8212; shows that Joseph is a type but not an exact copy; the antitype (Christ) will differ at significant points.</p>",
"7": "<p>And after a while his master&#8217;s wife took notice of Joseph and said, &#8220;Come to bed with me!&#8221; &#8212; the temptation of the covenant-bearer by the master&#8217;s wife. The tempter who uses the language of consent and desire to draw the covenant-bearer into sin is the type of the devil&#8217;s temptation of Christ. &#8220;Then Jesus was led by the Spirit into the wilderness to be tempted by the devil&#8221; (Matt 4:1). The temptation comes in a context of privilege and success &#8212; not in poverty but at the height of Joseph&#8217;s stewardship. The devil tempts Christ not in obscurity but after the baptismal affirmation (&#8220;This is my Son, whom I love,&#8221; Matt 3:17). Temptation follows affirmation; the enemy attacks when the covenant-bearer is most visibly blessed.</p>",
"8": "<p>But he refused. &#8220;With me in charge, my master does not concern himself with anything in the house; everything he owns he has entrusted to my care&#8221; &#8212; Joseph&#8217;s refusal begins with the covenant-faithfulness argument: the trust placed in him makes the betrayal worse, not better. The one entrusted with everything cannot betray the entrustor without destroying the foundation of the relationship. Christ&#8217;s faithfulness is precisely this: &#8220;Christ is faithful as the Son over God&#8217;s house&#8221; (Heb 3:6); &#8220;This is the one God has accredited&#8221; (Acts 2:22). The trusted steward who refuses to betray the trust is the type of the Son who is &#8220;faithful to the one who appointed him, just as Moses was faithful in all God&#8217;s house&#8221; (Heb 3:2). The refusal of sin on the grounds of faithfulness to the one who trusts.</p>",
"9": "<p>&#8220;No one is greater in this house than I am. My master has withheld nothing from me except you, because you are his wife. How then could I do this great evil and sin against God?&#8221; &#8212; Joseph&#8217;s refusal reaches its climax: &#8220;How then could I do this great evil and sin against God?&#8221; The sin is named not primarily as a sin against Potiphar (though it is that) but as a sin against God. The primary orientation of Joseph&#8217;s moral life is toward God rather than toward social consequences. David uses the same framing in Ps 51:4: &#8220;Against you, you only, have I sinned.&#8221; Christ&#8217;s entire life is oriented God-ward: &#8220;I always do what pleases him&#8221; (John 8:29). The moral refusal that names the act as first a sin against God is the mark of the covenant-bearer&#8217;s character.</p>",
"10": "<p>And though she spoke to Joseph day after day, he refused to go to bed with her or even to be with her &#8212; the repeated daily temptation that Joseph refuses day after day. The persistent temptation overcome by persistent refusal is the type of Christ&#8217;s complete sinlessness: &#8220;we have one who has been tempted in every way, just as we are &#8212; yet he did not sin&#8221; (Heb 4:15). The &#8220;in every way&#8221; encompasses the persistent, repeated nature of temptation: not a single great test but daily, relentless pressure. Joseph&#8217;s daily refusal &#8212; refusing &#8220;to go to bed with her or even to be with her&#8221; &#8212; shows the full scope of the avoidance: not merely the act but the occasion. Jesus flees the crowd&#8217;s attempt to make him king (John 6:15); he avoids the occasions of compromise as well as the acts.</p>",
"11": "<p>One day he went into the house to attend to his duties, and none of the household servants was inside &#8212; the circumstances of isolation that the tempter exploits. Joseph goes about his ordinary duties; the occasion of vulnerability comes in the ordinary course of work, not in any unusual situation. The tempter exploits ordinary moments: &#8220;your adversary the devil prowls around like a roaring lion, seeking someone to devour&#8221; (1 Pet 5:8). The ordinary moment of isolation &#8212; &#8220;none of the household servants was inside&#8221; &#8212; is the occasion the enemy chooses. Christ was tempted in the wilderness, in an isolated place, apart from community. The isolation that makes temptation easier is not avoided by those who must do their daily work; it is faced and overcome.</p>",
"12": "<p>She caught him by his cloak and said, &#8220;Come to bed with me!&#8221; But he left his cloak in her hand and ran out of the house &#8212; Joseph&#8217;s flight from temptation. He does not negotiate; he runs. The cloak left behind is the cost of the flight. Paul&#8217;s instruction: &#8220;Flee from sexual immorality&#8221; (1 Cor 6:18); &#8220;Flee the evil desires of youth&#8221; (2 Tim 2:22). The cost of fleeing is the cloak &#8212; something is left behind, something is lost. But the loss of the cloak is nothing compared to the gain of integrity. Joseph&#8217;s flight is the type of the believer&#8217;s battle with temptation: not to stand and reason but to flee and leave behind what the tempter grasps at. The cloak that remains in the enemy&#8217;s hand will become the false evidence &#8212; but the one who fled is innocent.</p>",
"13": "<p>When she saw that he had left his cloak in her hand and had run out of the house &#8212; the moment when the attempt at temptation becomes the occasion for false accusation. The tempter who is refused becomes the accuser. The structural parallel to Satan as &#8220;the accuser of our brothers and sisters, who accuses them before our God day and night&#8221; (Rev 12:10) is embedded in this narrative: the one who tempted becomes the one who accuses. The refused temptation triggers the false charge. Christ was falsely accused by those who could not successfully tempt him: the religious leaders who failed to trap him with questions then used false witnesses at his trial (Matt 26:59&#8211;61). Temptation failed &#8594; false accusation &#8594; unjust judgment: the pattern of the passion.</p>",
"14": "<p>She called her household servants. &#8220;Look,&#8221; she said to them, &#8220;this Hebrew has been brought to us to make sport of us! He came in here to sleep with me, but I screamed&#8221; &#8212; the false accusation constructed from the abandoned cloak. The accusation inverts the truth entirely: the one who refused is accused of attempt; the one who was innocent is presented as guilty. The false witness that inverts the truth is what the chief priests and the whole Sanhedrin used at Jesus&#8217;s trial: &#8220;They were looking for false testimony&#8230; but they did not find any&#8221; (Matt 26:59&#8211;60, though eventually two false witnesses were found). The righteous one condemned by a construction of lies from physical evidence is the type of Christ&#8217;s trial.</p>",
"15": "<p>&#8220;When he heard me scream for help, he left his cloak beside me and ran out of the house&#8221; &#8212; the false narrative built around the real cloak. The real evidence (the cloak) supports the false story: the physical truth becomes the carrier of the narrative lie. The passion narrative similarly uses real facts to support a false verdict: Jesus really was seen in the temple (the disciples confirm it); he really did speak of destroying and rebuilding the temple (John 2:19); these truths are twisted into &#8220;I am able to destroy the temple of God and rebuild it in three days&#8221; (Matt 26:61) &#8212; a misrepresentation used as a false accusation. The real evidence in a false framing is the structure of the unjust accusation against both Joseph and Christ.</p>",
"16": "<p>She kept his cloak beside her until his master came home &#8212; Potiphar&#8217;s wife keeps the cloak as preserved evidence. The maintained accusation &#8212; the deliberately preserved false evidence &#8212; is the type of the sustained hostility that awaited Jesus throughout his ministry: &#8220;the Pharisees went out and began to plot with the Herodians how they might kill Jesus&#8221; (Mark 3:6). The cloak kept as a weapon until the moment of confrontation is the type of the sustained accusation that precedes a show trial. The covenant-bearer who is innocent faces not a spontaneous accusation but a sustained, prepared one.</p>",
"17": "<p>Then she told him this story: &#8220;That Hebrew slave you brought us came to me to make sport of me&#8221; &#8212; the false accusation delivered to Potiphar in the form of a narrative (&#8220;this story&#8221; &#8212; the text uses the word sipper, narrative/account). The constructed narrative that reframes the events in a false light is the type of the false testimony at Jesus&#8217;s trial: the events of the temple-cleansing and Jesus&#8217;s saying about the temple are woven into a false narrative (Matt 26:61). The false narrative that harms the innocent is what Ps 27:12 cries out against: &#8220;Do not turn me over to the desire of my foes, for false witnesses rise up against me, spouting malicious accusations.&#8221; Christ is the fulfillment of this Psalm in his trial.</p>",
"18": "<p>&#8220;But as soon as I screamed for help, he left his cloak beside me and ran out of the house&#8221; &#8212; the false narrative&#8217;s conclusion. The accusation ends with the cloak as physical evidence &#8212; the one piece of objective evidence that seems to confirm the entire false story. The physical evidence that seems to confirm the false narrative: at Jesus&#8217;s arrest, the disciples flee (Matt 26:56: &#8220;Then all the disciples deserted him and fled&#8221;); Jesus is alone among enemies, exactly as the accusers want. The physical facts of abandonment and isolation seem to confirm the accusation&#8217;s framing. The innocent one surrounded by seeming confirmation of the false charge is the Christ-type&#8217;s pattern.</p>",
"19": "<p>When his master heard the story his wife told him, saying, &#8220;This is how your slave treated me,&#8221; he burned with anger &#8212; Potiphar&#8217;s anger at the false accusation. The righteous-seeming anger of the judge who has been deceived is the type of the anger directed at Jesus by those who misunderstand: &#8220;They all condemned him as worthy of death&#8221; (Mark 14:64). The judges who condemn with genuine anger based on false information: the Sanhedrin genuinely believed (or claimed to believe) Jesus was a blasphemer; Potiphar genuinely believed (or appeared to believe) his wife. The unjust verdict delivered with genuine-seeming outrage is the consistent context of the covenant-bearer&#8217;s unjust suffering.</p>",
"20": "<p>Joseph&#8217;s master took him and put him in prison, the place where the king&#8217;s prisoners were confined. But while Joseph was there in the prison &#8212; the descent deepens: from the pit (37:24, thrown in by brothers) to slavery to prison. Each descent appears to be the end; each descent is actually the preparation for the next level of the divine purpose. The pattern of descent-through-imprisonment leading to exaltation is the Joseph Christ-type at its most structural: Phil 2:6&#8211;9 describes Christ&#8217;s descent (divine form &#8594; servant form &#8594; death &#8594; death on a cross) followed by ascent (exalted &#8594; name above every name &#8594; every knee bowing). Joseph&#8217;s pit &#8594; slavery &#8594; prison &#8594; exaltation as Pharaoh&#8217;s vizier is the OT&#8217;s most sustained narrative type of the Christ-descent-and-ascent pattern.</p>",
"21": "<p>But the LORD was with him; he showed him unfailing love and granted him favor in the eyes of the prison warden &#8212; &#8220;The LORD was with him&#8221; &#8212; the third occurrence in this chapter (vv2, 3, 21). Even in prison, the divine presence continues. The divine presence in the worst place is one of the OT&#8217;s most important theological claims: Ps 139:8: &#8220;If I make my bed in the depths, you are there.&#8221; The LORD shows Joseph hesed &#8212; covenant faithfulness, steadfast love &#8212; in the prison. Christ promises his presence specifically in the places of suffering: &#8220;For I was hungry and you gave me food, I was thirsty and you gave me drink, I was a stranger and you welcomed me, I was naked and you clothed me, I was sick and you visited me, I was in prison and you came to me&#8221; (Matt 25:35&#8211;36). Christ identifies with the imprisoned. The LORD&#8217;s presence with Joseph in prison is the type of Christ&#8217;s solidarity with the suffering.</p>",
"22": "<p>The warden put Joseph in charge of all those held in the prison, and he was made responsible for all that was done there &#8212; Joseph rises to authority even in prison. The same pattern as in Potiphar&#8217;s house (v4: &#8220;put him in charge of his household&#8221;): wherever Joseph is, he rises to stewardship through divine favor. The principle: &#8220;For whoever has will be given more, and they will have an abundance&#8221; (Matt 25:29). The faithful steward who is trusted with more in each place is the type of Christ as the one to whom &#8220;all authority in heaven and on earth&#8221; is given (Matt 28:18) &#8212; the ultimate exaltation of the one who proved faithful in every circumstance. Joseph in the prison is faithful; Christ in death is faithful (&#8220;into your hands I commit my spirit,&#8221; Luke 23:46) &#8212; and both are exalted.</p>",
"23": "<p>The warden paid no attention to anything under Joseph&#8217;s care, because the LORD was with Joseph and gave him success in whatever he did &#8212; the fourth &#8220;the LORD was with Joseph&#8221; concludes the chapter. The chapter began with Joseph&#8217;s involuntary descent into Egypt as a slave (v1) and ends with Joseph as a trusted steward even in prison (v23). The divine presence transforms every circumstance &#8212; not by removing the suffering but by making the sufferer fruitful and faithful within it. Paul from prison: &#8220;I can do all this through him who gives me strength&#8221; (Phil 4:13); &#8220;The Lord stood at my side and gave me strength&#8221; (2 Tim 4:17). The divine presence that makes the prisoner successful in whatever he does is the same presence Christ promises to those he sends into the world: &#8220;And surely I am with you always, to the very end of the age&#8221; (Matt 28:20).</p>",
},
"40": {
"1": "<p>Some time later, the cupbearer and the baker of the king of Egypt offended their master, the king of Egypt &#8212; two royal officials fall into disgrace and are imprisoned &#8212; both in the prison where Joseph is held. The cupbearer (who tastes and presents the king&#8217;s wine) and the baker (who prepares the king&#8217;s food) are figures of honor who have fallen into dishonor through offense against the king. The fall from royal favor to imprisonment is the human condition in the presence of the Holy King. Isaiah 6:5: &#8220;Woe to me! I am ruined! For I am a man of unclean lips&#8230; and my eyes have seen the King, the LORD Almighty.&#8221; Those who offend the King are subject to his judgment; those who find a mediator between themselves and the King find restoration. Joseph will be that mediator in the prison.</p>",
"2": "<p>Pharaoh was angry with his two officials, the chief cupbearer and the chief baker &#8212; Pharaoh&#8217;s anger at his officials places them under the threat of death (as v19 will confirm for the baker). The anger of the king that threatens death is the type of the divine holiness that threatens judgment: &#8220;our God is a consuming fire&#8221; (Heb 12:29). The two officials subject to the king&#8217;s anger need an intercessor who can mediate between them and the king&#8217;s wrath. Joseph will interpret dreams and thereby mediate knowledge of the king&#8217;s intentions. Christ is the ultimate intercessor: &#8220;he always lives to intercede for them&#8221; (Heb 7:25). The two officials who need someone to stand between them and the king&#8217;s anger are the type of all who need Christ&#8217;s mediation before the divine throne.</p>",
"3": "<p>And put them in custody in the house of the captain of the guard, in the same prison where Joseph was confined &#8212; the two offenders placed in the same prison as the innocent Joseph. The innocent one sharing the prison of those who have genuinely offended their master &#8212; &#8220;numbered with the transgressors&#8221; (Isa 53:12; Mark 15:28). Christ is &#8220;crucified between two criminals&#8221; (Luke 23:33) &#8212; the innocent one sharing the execution of those who were guilty. The placement of the innocent covenant-bearer in the prison of the guilty is the structural setup for the type: one criminal restored, one executed, the innocent one present with both and mediating the interpretation of both destinies.</p>",
"4": "<p>The captain of the guard assigned them to Joseph, and he attended them. After they had been in custody for some time &#8212; Joseph is assigned to serve the two imprisoned royal officials. The innocent prisoner serving the guilty prisoners &#8212; the posture of the servant who gives his service to those who are under judgment. Christ serves from his position among the condemned: from the cross he addresses both criminals (Luke 23:39&#8211;43) and promises paradise to the one who trusts him. The ministry to the imprisoned is both Joseph&#8217;s calling in Egypt and explicitly Christ&#8217;s identification: &#8220;I was in prison and you came to me&#8221; (Matt 25:36). The servant who attends to those under judgment is the posture of the one who came &#8220;not to condemn the world, but to save the world&#8221; (John 3:17).</p>",
"5": "<p>Each of the two men &#8212; the cupbearer and the baker &#8212; had a dream the same night, and each dream had a meaning of its own &#8212; the simultaneous dreams &#8212; one for each man, each with its own distinct meaning. The divine communication through dreams is the OT&#8217;s regular channel of revelation (Gen 28:12; 37:5&#8211;11; Num 12:6). The same night, the same divine source, two different dreams with two different meanings &#8212; the type of the same gospel encounter that produces two different responses: one to life, one to death. The same Christ preached is &#8220;to one an aroma of death leading to death, and to the other an aroma of life leading to life&#8221; (2 Cor 2:16). The simultaneous revelation that divides two hearers into two destinies is the eschatological pattern that the prison dreams begin to trace.</p>",
"6": "<p>When Joseph came to them the next morning, he saw that they were dejected &#8212; Joseph notices the prisoners&#8217; dejected state before they speak. The pastoral attentiveness that reads the sadness of others before they express it is the type of Christ&#8217;s compassion: &#8220;When Jesus saw her weeping, and the Jews who had come with her also weeping, he was deeply moved in spirit and troubled&#8221; (John 11:33). &#8220;When he saw the crowds, he had compassion on them&#8221; (Matt 9:36). The one who notices the suffering of others while himself imprisoned and suffering is the type of Christ&#8217;s solidarity with the suffering: he &#8220;sympathize[s] with our weaknesses&#8221; (Heb 4:15) from within his own experience of weakness. Joseph&#8217;s pastoral seeing from within the prison is the type of Christ&#8217;s compassionate seeing from within the incarnation.</p>",
"7": "<p>So he asked Pharaoh&#8217;s officials who were in custody with him in his master&#8217;s house, &#8220;Why do you look so sad today?&#8221; &#8212; the question Joseph asks is the question of the one who cares about the answer. &#8220;Why do you look so sad today?&#8221; is the diagnostic question of the pastor/healer. Christ asks similar diagnostic questions: &#8220;What do you want me to do for you?&#8221; (Matt 20:32, to the blind men); &#8220;Do you want to get well?&#8221; (John 5:6, to the paralyzed man). The question is not information-gathering (Joseph can see they are sad) but the opening of the relationship that allows the person to voice the need. Christ&#8217;s questions invite self-disclosure as the first step toward help; Joseph&#8217;s question opens the conversation that will result in interpretation and salvation for one of the two.</p>",
"8": "<p>&#8220;We both had dreams,&#8221; they answered, &#8220;but there is no one to interpret them.&#8221; Then Joseph said to them, &#8220;Do not interpretations belong to God? Tell me your dreams&#8221; &#8212; &#8220;Do not interpretations belong to God?&#8221; &#8212; Joseph&#8217;s immediate deflection of the gift to the divine source. The prophet who attributes his interpretive gift to God is the type of Christ who consistently attributes his authority and knowledge to the Father: &#8220;My teaching is not my own. It comes from the one who sent me&#8221; (John 7:16); &#8220;the Son can do nothing by himself; he can do only what he sees his Father doing&#8221; (John 5:19). The human interpreter through whom God speaks does not claim the gift for himself. Joseph in prison, claiming no glory for the gift, is the type of the one who &#8220;did not consider equality with God something to be used to his own advantage&#8221; (Phil 2:6).</p>",
"9": "<p>So the chief cupbearer told Joseph his dream. He said to him, &#8220;In my dream I saw a vine in front of me&#8221; &#8212; the vine &#8212; the symbol of Israel in the OT (Ps 80:8: &#8220;You transplanted a vine from Egypt&#8221;; Isa 5:1&#8211;7: the Song of the Vineyard). Christ identifies himself as &#8220;the true vine&#8221; (John 15:1&#8211;5): &#8220;I am the true vine, and my Father is the gardener.&#8221; The vine in the cupbearer&#8217;s dream produces grapes that become wine for the king&#8217;s cup &#8212; the type of Christ who is himself the vine that produces the fruit of the Spirit, the wine of the new covenant: &#8220;I tell you, I will not drink from this fruit of the vine from now on until that day when I drink it new with you in my Father&#8217;s kingdom&#8221; (Matt 26:29). The vine in the dream points to the one who is the vine.</p>",
"10": "<p>&#8220;And on the vine were three branches. As soon as it budded, it blossomed, and its clusters ripened into grapes&#8221; &#8212; the three branches, the budding, blossoming, and ripening. The fruitfulness of the vine &#8212; rapid, complete, moving from bud to ripe grape &#8212; is the type of the eschatological fruitfulness that comes through Christ the true vine: &#8220;I am the vine; you are the branches. If you remain in me and I in you, you will bear much fruit&#8221; (John 15:5). The rapid, complete movement from bud to ripe grape is the type of the gospel&#8217;s power to produce fruit quickly in those who receive it: &#8220;the word of God&#8230; is bearing fruit and growing throughout the whole world&#8221; (Col 1:6).</p>",
"11": "<p>&#8220;Pharaoh&#8217;s cup was in my hand, and I took the grapes, squeezed them into Pharaoh&#8217;s cup and put the cup in his hand&#8221; &#8212; the cupbearer&#8217;s role: to put the cup in the king&#8217;s hand. The cup presented to the king by the servant is the type of the cup that is central to the new covenant: &#8220;This cup is the new covenant in my blood&#8221; (Luke 22:20; 1 Cor 11:25). Christ himself takes the cup: &#8220;Shall I not drink the cup the Father has given me?&#8221; (John 18:11). The servant who presents the cup to the king &#8212; the cup of blessing and favor &#8212; is the type of Christ who presents to the Father the cup of his own blood as the new covenant&#8217;s seal. The cupbearer&#8217;s dream contains the symbol of the Last Supper and the cross.</p>",
"12": "<p>&#8220;This is what it means,&#8221; Joseph said to him. &#8220;The three branches are three days&#8221; &#8212; Joseph&#8217;s interpretation: the three branches = three days. The three-day interpretive key recurs throughout the Joseph narrative: three days here, three days for the brothers in custody (42:17), three days before the good news. Three days is the consistent unit of the decisive divine intervention in the OT and NT: Jonah three days in the fish (Jonah 1:17; Matt 12:40); three days of darkness in Egypt (Exod 10:22&#8211;23); and above all, Christ&#8217;s three days in the tomb: &#8220;After three days I will rise again&#8221; (Matt 27:63; Mark 8:31). The three-branch/three-day equation that Joseph offers is the OT&#8217;s clearest numerical type of the resurrection interval.</p>",
"13": "<p>&#8220;Within three days Pharaoh will lift up your head and restore you to your position, and you will put Pharaoh&#8217;s cup in his hand, just as you used to do when you were his cupbearer&#8221; &#8212; the interpretation: &#8220;within three days&#8230; restore you to your position.&#8221; The restoration to the original position after three days is the resurrection type. The lifted head, the restored position, the return to the original function &#8212; all of these describe Christ&#8217;s resurrection: exalted to the &#8220;name that is above every name&#8221; (Phil 2:9), restored to the glory he had &#8220;before the world began&#8221; (John 17:5). The cupbearer who was under judgment and is restored to full function after three days is one of the clearest OT types of the resurrection&#8217;s structure: descent into death, three days, restoration to the original position of glory.</p>",
"14": "<p>&#8220;But when all goes well with you, remember me and show me kindness; mention me to Pharaoh and get me out of this prison&#8221; &#8212; Joseph&#8217;s request: &#8220;remember me.&#8221; The imprisoned innocent one&#8217;s plea to the one being restored. The thief on the cross: &#8220;Jesus, remember me when you come into your kingdom&#8221; (Luke 23:42) &#8212; the request to be remembered by the one being elevated. The parallel is exact: an innocent one in prison asks the one being lifted up to &#8220;mention me&#8221; to the king. Joseph asks the cupbearer to mention him to Pharaoh; the thief asks Jesus to remember him when he enters his kingdom. The cupbearer forgets (v23); Jesus does not: &#8220;Truly I tell you, today you will be with me in paradise&#8221; (Luke 23:43). Christ never forgets those who ask to be remembered.</p>",
"15": "<p>&#8220;I was forcibly carried off from the land of the Hebrews, and even here I have done nothing to deserve being put in a dungeon&#8221; &#8212; Joseph&#8217;s declaration of innocence: &#8220;I have done nothing to deserve being put in a dungeon.&#8221; The righteous sufferer&#8217;s declaration of innocence from the prison is the type of Christ&#8217;s innocence throughout his trial. Pilate&#8217;s triple declaration: &#8220;I find no basis for a charge against this man&#8221; (Luke 23:4, 14, 22); the criminal on the cross: &#8220;This man has done nothing wrong&#8221; (Luke 23:41); the centurion: &#8220;Surely this man was the Son of God&#8221; (Mark 15:39). The testimony to the innocent sufferer&#8217;s innocence from every direction &#8212; from the judge, the criminal, the soldier &#8212; mirrors Joseph&#8217;s own declaration of innocence. Both are unjustly imprisoned; both are declared innocent by their own testimony and by others.</p>",
"16": "<p>When the chief baker saw that Joseph had given a favorable interpretation, he said to Joseph, &#8220;I too had a dream: On my head were three baskets of bread&#8221; &#8212; the baker&#8217;s dream, prompted by the cupbearer&#8217;s favorable interpretation. The baker&#8217;s confidence in seeking interpretation after hearing the favorable verdict given to the cupbearer reflects the human tendency to expect favorable news. The two criminals at the cross both initially mock Jesus (Matt 27:44); one changes and seeks mercy; the other continues in hostility. The baker&#8217;s expectation of a favorable verdict &#8212; based on the cupbearer&#8217;s experience &#8212; is the type of the presumptuous faith that expects grace without repentance. The same interpreter who gives life to one pronounces death on the other; the difference is not in the interpreter but in the one being interpreted.</p>",
"17": "<p>&#8220;In the top basket were all kinds of baked goods for Pharaoh, but the birds were eating them out of the basket on my head&#8221; &#8212; the birds eating the bread intended for the king. The despoiling of what should have been presented to the king is the sign of the baker&#8217;s failed stewardship. The one entrusted to bring food to the king whose offering is spoiled before it arrives &#8212; the type of the worship that never reaches God because it is intercepted by the enemy. Christ warns about this: in the parable of the sower, &#8220;when anyone hears the message about the kingdom and does not understand it, the evil one comes and snatches away what was sown&#8221; (Matt 13:19). The birds in the dream &#8212; eating the bread meant for the king &#8212; are the type of the enemy who snatches the word before it reaches its destination.</p>",
"18": "<p>&#8220;This is what it means,&#8221; Joseph said. &#8220;The three baskets are three days&#8221; &#8212; the same three-day interpretation, but with a different outcome. The same three days that bring restoration for the cupbearer bring death for the baker. The identical time-unit produces two opposite outcomes: resurrection-type for one, death-sentence for the other. &#8220;The hour is coming when all who are in their graves will hear his voice and come out &#8212; those who have done what is good will rise to live, and those who have done what is evil will rise to be condemned&#8221; (John 5:28&#8211;29). The same event &#8212; the resurrection &#8212; produces two outcomes based not on the power of the event but on the condition of the recipient. The three days of the cupbearer&#8217;s dream and the three days of the baker&#8217;s dream are identical; what differs is what the three days mean for each.</p>",
"19": "<p>&#8220;Within three days Pharaoh will lift off your head and impale your body on a pole. And the birds will eat away your flesh&#8221; &#8212; the unfavorable interpretation: &#8220;lift off your head&#8221; (not &#8220;lift up your head&#8221; as in v13). The same phrase used positively for the cupbearer (&#8220;lift up your head&#8221; = restore to honor) used negatively for the baker (&#8220;lift off your head&#8221; = execution). The cross has two aspects in the same way: &#8220;When I am lifted up from the earth, I will draw all people to myself&#8221; (John 12:32) &#8212; the lifting up of Christ on the cross is simultaneously his exaltation (resurrection/ascension) and his death. One criminal drawn to him in faith; one rejecting. The fate of the baker &#8212; impaled on a pole, devoured by birds &#8212; echoes the curses of Deut 28:26: the covenant-breaker&#8217;s body left for the birds. The two criminals crucified with Christ face the same fate: one redeemed, one in the covenant-breaker&#8217;s place.</p>",
"20": "<p>Now the third day was Pharaoh&#8217;s birthday, and he gave a feast for all his officials. He lifted up the heads of the chief cupbearer and the chief baker &#8212; on the third day, the birthday feast, the lifting of heads. The feast on the third day where judgment is pronounced is the eschatological banquet. Pharaoh&#8217;s birthday feast on the third day &#8212; the day of life-celebration &#8212; is also the day of the two officials&#8217; judgment: one restored to life at the celebration-feast, one executed. The final judgment has the same structure: the great feast of the Lamb (Rev 19:9: &#8220;Blessed are those who are invited to the wedding supper of the Lamb&#8221;) is simultaneous with the destruction of the beast (Rev 19:20). The feast of joy and the judgment of condemnation occur together on the &#8220;third day&#8221; of God&#8217;s redemptive calendar.</p>",
"21": "<p>He restored the chief cupbearer to his position, so that he once again put the cup into Pharaoh&#8217;s hand &#8212; the cupbearer restored: he puts the cup in Pharaoh&#8217;s hand again, exactly as before. The restoration to the original function &#8212; not to a different role but to the precise original position &#8212; is the resurrection type. Christ&#8217;s resurrection is not a transition to a different mode of existence but a restoration to glorious life: &#8220;This same Jesus, who has been taken from you into heaven, will come back in the same way you have seen him go&#8221; (Acts 1:11). The same body, the same identity, the same function &#8212; but now glorified. The cupbearer restored to his cup is the type of the resurrection body: the same person doing the same work, now in the context of the king&#8217;s restored favor.</p>",
"22": "<p>But he impaled the chief baker, just as Joseph had said would happen &#8212; the baker&#8217;s execution, fulfilling Joseph&#8217;s interpretation exactly. The exact fulfillment of the prophetic word is one of the NT&#8217;s primary evidences for the Messianic identity of Jesus: &#8220;This took place to fulfill what was spoken through the prophet&#8221; (Matt 1:22; 2:15, 17, 23; 4:14, etc. &#8212; the formula recurs throughout Matthew). Joseph&#8217;s two-prophecy fulfillment on the third day &#8212; both interpretations confirmed exactly as predicted &#8212; establishes Joseph as a reliable prophet of divine will. The reliability of the divine word through the prophet is confirmed when both predictions come true: &#8220;If what a prophet proclaims in the name of the LORD does not take place or come true, that is a message the LORD has not spoken&#8221; (Deut 18:22). Joseph&#8217;s word comes true for both; Christ&#8217;s word comes true for all.</p>",
"23": "<p>The chief cupbearer, however, did not remember Joseph; he forgot him &#8212; the cupbearer&#8217;s forgetting &#8212; the chapter&#8217;s final word and the human story&#8217;s persistent tragedy. The one who was saved forgets the one who saved him. This is one of the OT&#8217;s most consistent complaints: Ps 106:13: &#8220;But they soon forgot what he had done and did not wait for his plan to unfold.&#8221; &#8220;Was no one found to return and give praise to God except this foreigner?&#8221; (Luke 17:18). The ingratitude of the healed is the human constant. But the cupbearer&#8217;s forgetting is not the end: Pharaoh&#8217;s dream will force the memory two years later (41:9&#8211;13). God&#8217;s purposes are not defeated by human forgetfulness &#8212; they simply wait for the moment when the forgotten one must be remembered. Christ is not defeated by being forgotten; he waits for the moment when every knee will bow and every tongue confess (Phil 2:10&#8211;11).</p>",
},
}

